                        Text:  Volcanic domes usually form in the aftermath of powerful explosions at composite cones, such as at Mt. St. Helens in 1980.  A decade after this eruption the new dome continued to grow inside the volcano's crater.  One of the greatest hazards associated with explosive volcanism is dense clouds of hot ash, which roar down volcanic slopes into low lying areas, sometimes at well over a hundred kilometers per hour.
